      },
      "http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#comment": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "In Plato interpretation of the hermaphrodite, two opposites, men and women, share the same body forming a union. Eventually they are punished and separated through a traumatic cut, which lead the two parts to search for one another for the rest of their lives, recalling the mystical structure described by Durand."
